{"type":"message","id":"3819a47d","parentId":"d9497e71","timestamp":"2026-03-19T17:15:41.256Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still only 2 agents. The backend seems to only keep one remote agent. The same agentId is being reused for all joins. This might be a backend bug where the joinKey \"ocj_pm_01\" overwrote the previous one, or the backend only supports one remote agent at a time.\n\nActually, looking at the join-keys.json, the key \"ocj_pm_01\" was used and now it's the one registered. The previous ones (finance_01, newsai_01, coder_01) were overwritten.\n\nWait - the join API is probably treating all joins as the same agent (or updating the same agent). The same agentId being returned every time suggests the backend is either:\n\n\n1. Not creating new agents for different join keys\n2. Deduplicating by some criteria\n\nThis looks like a backend limitation. Let me check if there's a way to push state directly without joining, or if I need to configure the OFFICE_URL differently for each agent. Actually, looking at the office-agent-push.py script more carefully, I think the issue might be that the office-agent-push.py saves the agentId locally, so when the same script joins multiple times, it might be reusing the same agentId instead of creating separate agents for each join key.\n\nBut I've already modified the scripts for each agent and they should each be running separately. The problem is likely that the state.json file on the local machine is being read by the backend, and since all agents are on the same machine, they're all reading from the same state file instead of their own isolated configurations. Plus, the backend might have a bug where it only tracks one remote agent at a time since all joins return the same agentId. Let me verify the backend is actually running and check if there's a state persistence issue with the join-keys.json file. Looking at the join response, all three agents received the same agentId, which suggests either the backend is overwriting entries when multiple join requests happen simultaneously, or there's deduplication logic that's collapsing them into one agent.\n\nI'm realizing the issue might be simpler - the PowerShell encoding for Chinese characters could be garbling the name field in the API requests, though the JSON itself should handle Unicode fine. The fact that the API returned success for all three join attempts but they all got the same agentId points to a backend deduplication problem rather than a request encoding issue.\n\nRather than continue debugging the join mechanism, I should try directly invoking the agent push endpoint with distinct agent IDs for each agent and see if that bypasses whatever deduplication is happening on the server side. But actually, stepping back - the join API is clearly meant for one agent to enter the office, so the right approach is to run the actual office-agent-push.py script for each agent, not try to manually call the API. Let me look at what the push mechanism is actually supposed to do. The join API returned the same agentId for different joinKeys, which suggests the backend might be returning a cached response or there's a server-side issue with how it's handling multiple agent registrations. I should try using POSTMAN or a different approach to make the requests, and check if there's an existing agents.json file that might be interfering with the registration process.","thinkingSignature":"387971a66dcbbd5bd8a80dcf3b201ef289c71d69d8553cf4375388c6cdea4484"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mxn8uev5q46z_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem \"C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\workspace\\Star-Office-UI\" -Filter \"*.json\" | Select-Object Name, Length; Get-ChildItem \"C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\workspace\\Star-Office-UI\\backend\" -Filter \"*.json\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object Name","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax",