{"type":"message","id":"2cd642c4","parentId":"f95021dc","timestamp":"2026-03-19T17:15:57.751Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! The backend only stores 2 agents: Star (local) + one remote agent. The other joinKeys (coder_01, newsai_01, finance_01) were overwritten because each join with a different joinKey replaces the previous remote agent. The \"name\" shows \"???\" because of encoding issues when the name was submitted.\n\nThis seems like the backend is designed to only have one remote agent at a time, OR there's a deduplication issue where it only keeps the latest join.\n\nLooking at the office-agent-push.py, when it does a join, it saves the agentId to a local state file (office-agent-state.json) and then uses that agentId for subsequent pushes. \n\nSo if I run multiple instances of the script with different joinKeys, the backend should theoretically keep track of each one separately. But based on the agents-state.json showing only one remote agent with joinKey \"ocj_pm_01\", it appears the backend is actually overwriting the previous remote agent whenever a new one joins with a different key.\n\nThis could be a deliberate design choice where only the most recent remote agent persists, or it might be a bug in how the backend handles multiple concurrent join requests. The join response returning the same agentId for different keys suggests either the backend is overwriting previous agents on each join, or there's some deduplication happening server-side that I need to investigate by examining the backend code more closely.\n\nThe most straightforward solution would be to run separate instances of office-agent-push.py for each agent with distinct agent IDs, rather than trying to work around what might be a limitation in how the backend manages multiple remote agents.","thinkingSignature":"6c6af86038e27355b6ef7fa198ae5295167d3b3d8d8f8ee8dd8f976031731c67"},{"type":"text","text":"找到问题了——后端 `agents-state.json` 只保留了一个远程 ag