{"type":"message","id":"eee1d345","parentId":"b7d3cb5f","timestamp":"2026-03-19T17:17:19.178Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to:1. Clear agents-state.json to remove the corrupted entry2. Clear join-keys.json to reset\n3. Restart backend4. Create fresh join keys for each agent5. Launch the push scripts for each agentActually, looking at the scripts - they have `office-agent-state.json` in the SAME directory as `office-agent-push.py`. And since each agent has its own workspace, the state file would be:- C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\agents\\coder\\workspace\\office-agent-state.json\n- etc.\n\nBut the `state.json` (for the office state) is also in the same directory. And the backend reads from the root `state.json` in the Star-Office-UI folder. \n\nI should also update the join-keys.json to reset it. But I'm realizing the office-agent-push.py script uses a hardcoded path for the state file based on its own location, so each agent's workspace gets its own isolated state file. The real issue was the garbled Chinese characters in the API calls, not the state file itself.\n\nThe core problem is that when `Invoke-RestMethod` sends JSON with Unicode characters, the backend might not handle the encoding properly, which is why the names came back as \"???\". Running the Python script directly should handle the encoding correctly since Python's JSON library handles Unicode natively. Let me clear the agents-state.json and reset the join keys to get a fresh start, though I'm concerned the backend might have persisted the corrupted data.","thinkingSignature":"95166eedb4a465ac061597b513fafcda5f6c4c93a52ec3a869009f3d021c3566"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_sm4qwrjd43o7_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\workspace\\Star-Office-UI\\agents-state.json","content":"[]\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_sm4qwrjd43o7_2","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Adminis