{"type":"message","id":"0cf58082","parentId":"2a3c14e3","timestamp":"2026-03-19T17:22:15.411Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user says they can see the agents standing there but not their real-time status. The issue is that the agents joined the dashboard but are not pushing their status updates. The agents only joined once, but they're not continuously pushing their status.\n\nThe `office-agent-push.py` script should continuously push status every 15 seconds. But the agents are not running this script. We need to start the push scripts for each agent.\n\nHowever, starting background Python processes for each agent from within this session might be tricky. Each push script needs to run in its own process, persistently.\n\nLet me think about how to start these background processes. I can use `Start-Process` to start each Python script as a background process for each agent workspace.\n \nWait, I need to reconsider—the agents aren't separate processes I can spawn. Each agent is just a configuration in OpenClaw, so the real question is how to get their status reflected on the dashboard. The `office-agent-push.py` script reads from a state file and pushes that to the dashboard, so I need to create a state file for each agent and then figure out how to continuously update it.\n\nThe challenge is that OpenClaw agents don't automatically update a shared state file. I'd need to either run `set_state.py` to manually update the state file and trigger pushes, or find another way to get the agent's current status to the dashboard.\n\nLooking at how the script works, it reads from the shared `state.json` file in the Star-Office-UI directory, and since all agents have access to that location, they'd all be reading and writing to the same file. This means whichever agent updates the file last would overwrite the others' status.\n\nThe core issue is that OpenClaw agents don't automatically update `state.json` when their status changes—I